  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "Here's an overview of the legal history of money laundering prohibitions:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Informal anti-money laundering (AML) practices existed as early as the 1920s\n- Initial efforts were primarily focused on combating organized crime and tax evasion\n\n2. Bank Secrecy Act (1970) - United States:\n- First comprehensive legal framework addressing financial recordkeeping\n- Required financial institutions to report large currency transactions\n- Established reporting requirements to detect potential criminal activities\n\n3. International Development:\n- 1980s: Growing international recognition of money laundering as a global problem\n- Increased focus on drug trafficking proceeds and organized crime\n\n4. Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Establishment (1989):\n- Intergovernmental organization developing international AML standards\n- Created comprehensive recommendations for global financial regulations\n\n5. Key Legislative Milestones:\n- U.S. Money Laundering Control Act (1986)\n- U.S. Bank Secrecy Act Amendments (1992)\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001) - Significantly expanded AML regulations\n- Enhanced international cooperation and information sharing\n\n6. Expanded Scope:\n- From drug trafficking to broader criminal activities\n- Terrorism financing prevention\n- Increased global regulatory frameworks\n\nThis progression represents a complex, evolving legal approach to combating financial crimes.",
